# Test Conventions

## Stack
- `pytest` + `pytest-asyncio` (asyncio_mode = "auto")
- `pytest-homeassistant-custom-component` for HA internals
- `pytest-socket` to block unintended network access
- `unittest.mock` (AsyncMock, MagicMock, patch)

On **Windows**, `tests/conftest.py` uses a `pytest_fixture_setup` hookwrapper so `pytest_socket.enable_socket()` runs immediately before the `event_loop` fixture — `pytest-homeassistant-custom-component` disables sockets before fixtures run, which would otherwise break asyncio’s self-pipe. Linux/macOS are unaffected.

## Test layout mirrors source
```
tests/
  conftest.py          shared fixtures (mock_hass, mock_config_entry, sample_apps, mock_session)
  test_config_flow.py
  test_coordinator.py
  test_media_player.py (future)
  test_remote.py       (future)
  tizen/
    test_caps.py
    test_power_fsm.py
    test_ws_client.py
    test_key_sender.py
    test_app_manager.py
```

## Fixture conventions
- `mock_hass` — minimal MagicMock with `loop.call_later`, `bus.async_fire`, `config_entries.async_update_entry`
- `mock_config_entry` — MagicMock with `.data` dict matching real config-entry schema
- `sample_apps` — short list of 4 apps covering app_type 2 and 4
- `mock_session` — AsyncMock aiohttp.ClientSession

## What to test
- `caps.py` — all generation prefix boundaries
- `power_fsm.py` — all valid and invalid transitions
- `ws_client.py` — token extraction, unauthorized handling, app list parsing, send_key
- `key_sender.py` — count, clear, ordering
- `app_manager.py` — resolution (id / name / logical key / fallback), launch routing (WS vs REST)
- `coordinator.py` — FSM transitions, token persistence, key guard, listener notification
- `config_flow.py` — detect_tv: ok / cannot_connect / unsupported_model

## What NOT to test
- Internal HA framework wiring (entity registration, platform setup)
- Actual network calls — always mock aiohttp and asyncio timers
- Timer scheduling internals — test the *effects* of timer callbacks, not the scheduling itself
